*****
[4] Indonesia
Date Mon 9 May 2022
Source: WTVB [edited]
https://wtvbam.com/2022/05/09/indonesia-detects-15-cases-of-severe-hepatitis-after-3-child-deaths/


Indonesia has identified 15 cases of severe hepatitis of unknown origin after reporting 3 deaths among children, the country's health minister Budi Gunadi Sadikin told a news briefing on [Mon 9 May 2022]. The WHO said last week that it had received reports of at least 228 probable cases from 20 countries of child hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver.

Minister Budi said Indonesia had detected 15 cases since it launched an investigation into the illness recently, adding that authorities had not determined a definitive cause. He did not say whether the 15 cases were all children or what treatment they were receiving. A health ministry spokesperson did not immediately respond to a request for comment.

Some health experts have linked the illness to an infection by a type of adenovirus, a family of common viruses that can cause flu-like or gastrointestinal symptoms. There is also a theory that COVID-19 lockdowns may have weakened children's immunity because they were less exposed to common pathogens while in isolation. Scientists are in addition looking at whether the adenovirus involved has mutated, or is acting in tandem with another infection, possibly COVID-19.

Earlier this month [May 2022], Indonesia reported 3 children suspected to have contracted the illness had died in the capital Jakarta in April 2022.

[Byline: Stanley Widianto]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[More cases are being reported. Likely updates will occur in the next few days from CDC and UKHSA. It remains to be seen whether all of the cases are due to one etiology or not.

- Adenovirus type 41, one of the enteric adenoviruses, has been found in the blood of many of the cases but has not been known to cause hepatitis in immunocompetent people and was not found using metagenomics in the liver. It is not yet known whether type 41 is similar to older isolates of this adenovirus serotype.

- SARS-CoV-2 can cause hepatitis which may be much more prominent in children with MIS-C (multisystem inflammatory disease in children). Only some of the children were actively infected with this virus at the time of the hepatitis but no substantial data has yet been published regarding past infection with SARS-CoV-2 as some cases of MIS-C are thought to be late sequelae or whether the cases actually fit the multi-system disease.

- Adeno-associated virus 2 was found in some cases in the liver as reported by UKHSA but it has been known to cause hepatitis in humans and may be just reactivating the latent genome which can integrate into the human genome.

- A possible link to dog ownership has also been suggested by UKHSA.

ProMED awaits more information about this entity. - Mod.LL

